    <h5 class="mb-2 mt-4">Check if user has particular permission.</h5>
    <div class="d-flex justify-content-start mt-0">
        <h5 class="rounded mt-2 mb-5 p-3 custom-back">if request.user.has_perm('app_name.PermissionName'):</h5>
    </div>
    <hr />
    <h2 class="my-5 custom-title">Example</h2>
    <div class="d-flex justify-content-start mt-0">
        <h5 class="rounded mt-2 mb-5 p-3 custom-back">if request.user.has_perm('blogs.add'):</h5>
    </div>
    <hr />
    <h2 class="my-5 custom-title">Create your own permission</h2>
    <div class="rounded p-4 mt-4 mb-5 custom-div">
        <p class="mb-1">from app-name.models import model-name</p>
        <p class="mb-1">from django.contrib.auth.models import Permission</p>
        <p class="mb-1">from django.contrib.contenttypes.models import ContentType</p>
        <p class="mb-1">content_type = ContentType.objects.get_for_model(model-name)</p>
        <p class="mb-1">permission = Permission.objects.create(</p>
        <p class="mb-1 mr-25">codename='',</p>
        <p class="mb-1 mr-25">name='',</p>
        <p class="mb-1 mr-25">content_type=content_type,</p>
        <p class="mb-1">)</p>
    </div>
    <br>
    <hr />
    <h2 class="my-5 custom-title">Explanation</h2>
    <h5 class="mt-4 mb-5">
        content_type: define to which model you will insert the permission.
        codename: unique identifier for the permission.
        name: human-readable name for the permission.
        It's used to display the permission's purpose to administrators and users.
    </h5>
